## Summary
In a Feishu drive folder with more files than one API page, `feishu_drive` `action: info` returns a false `File not found: <token>` for any file that lives beyond the first page, and `action: list` cannot retrieve any page after the first. Both surfaces ignore the `has_more` / `next_page_token` cursor the Lark API returns, so files past page 1 are silently inaccessible.

## Environment
- Commit: cc451f98cbae5cb1db24cb3e97bced6d58952f57 (origin/main at time of filing)
- Surface: Feishu plugin `feishu_drive` tool, `list` and `info` actions (`extensions/feishu/src/drive.ts`, `extensions/feishu/src/drive-schema.ts`)

## Steps to reproduce
1. Have a Feishu drive folder with more files than fit in one `drive.file.list` page (the API signals this with `has_more: true` and a `next_page_token`).
2. Call `feishu_drive` `action: info` with the `file_token` of a file that sorts onto page 2 or later.
3. Or call `feishu_drive` `action: list` on that folder and try to fetch the next page.

## Expected
- `info` follows `has_more` / `next_page_token` until it finds the file, then returns its metadata.
- `list` accepts a page cursor so the caller can page through the whole folder, and reports whether more pages remain.

## Actual
- `info` searches only the first page and throws `File not found: <token>` for any file past page 1, even though the file exists and the API advertised more pages.
- `list` returns only the first page. The action schema exposes no `page_token`, so the returned `next_page_token` can never be fed back, and pages 2+ are unreachable.

## Root cause
`getFileInfo` (`extensions/feishu/src/drive.ts:356`) does a single first-page `.find()` and throws when absent, never following `has_more`:

```ts
async function getFileInfo(client: Lark.Client, fileToken: string, folderToken?: string) {
  // Use list with folder_token to find file info
  const res = await client.drive.file.list({
    params: folderToken ? { folder_token: folderToken } : {},
  });
  if (res.code !== 0) {
    throw new Error(res.msg);
  }

  const file = res.data?.files?.find((f) => f.token === fileToken);
  if (!file) {
    throw new Error(`File not found: ${fileToken}`);
  }
  // ...
}
```

`listFolder` (`extensions/feishu/src/drive.ts:331`) passes no `page_token` and the `list` action schema (`extensions/feishu/src/drive-schema.ts:25`) exposes none, so the `next_page_token` it does return at `drive.ts:352` can never be supplied on a follow-up call:

```ts
async function listFolder(client: Lark.Client, folderToken?: string) {
  const validFolderToken = folderToken && folderToken !== "0" ? folderToken : undefined;
  const res = await client.drive.file.list({
    params: validFolderToken ? { folder_token: validFolderToken } : {},
  });
  // ... returns next_page_token but the dispatch (drive.ts:770-773) accepts no cursor to send back
}
```

The Lark SDK `@larksuiteoapi/node-sdk` `drive.file.list` accepts `page_size` / `page_token` and returns `next_page_token` / `has_more` (and offers a `listWithIterator`). The plugin reads neither cursor field on this path.

## Sibling surfaces
This is the direct sibling-class of the just-merged wiki pagination fix #37626 (commit 5f90f08957), which paginated `wiki.spaceNode.list` / `wiki.space.list` in `wiki.ts` + `wiki-schema.ts` but did not touch `drive.ts`. The same plugin's comment paths already paginate correctly: `list_comments` and `list_comment_replies` expose `page_size` + `page_token` in the schema (`drive-schema.ts:54-66`) and read `has_more` / `page_token` from the response (`drive.ts:486-487`, `519-520`). So the drive `list` / `info` omission is the lone un-paginated lister in the plugin. Checked the open Feishu PRs (tool-family gates, card/proactive send, topic queue, audit redaction, URL challenge, streaming card coalescing); none touch drive `list` / `info`.

## Real behavior proof
Behavior addressed: `feishu_drive` `info` must find a file that lives past the first `drive.file.list` page instead of falsely reporting `File not found`.
Real environment tested: real `registerFeishuDriveTools` runtime driven end to end through the tool's `execute` dispatch and `getFileInfo`, with `client.drive.file.list` mocked to return the target on page 2 with `has_more: true` + `next_page_token`, at commit cc451f98cbae.
Exact steps or command run after this patch: `node scripts/run-vitest.mjs extensions/feishu/src/drive.pagination.repro.test.ts` (the repro registers the real drive tool, calls `action: info` for a token that sorts to page 2, and asserts the lister is drained to 2 pages and the file is returned).
Evidence after fix:
```
# OBSERVED (buggy, origin/main cc451f98cbae)
 FAIL  extensions/feishu/src/drive.pagination.repro.test.ts > info finds a file that lives past the first page
 AssertionError: expected "vi.fn()" to be called 2 times, but got 1 times
   115|     expect(listMock).toHaveBeenCalledTimes(2);
       |                      ^
 -> getFileInfo queried only page 1 (one list call) and threw "File not found: target";
    list was never asked for page 2 despite has_more: true.

# EXPECTED (correct behavior on identical inputs, with the local fix applied)
 Test Files  2 passed (2)
      Tests  16 passed (16)
 -> getFileInfo drains has_more/next_page_token to page 2 (two list calls), finds and
    returns the file. Existing drive.test.ts stays green (15 tests), 16 total.
```
Observed result after fix: on unmodified main, info silently fails for files past page 1 (list called once, throws File not found); draining pages following has_more/next_page_token fixes it without regressing existing drive behavior.
What was not tested: not run against a live Feishu tenant; the proof drives the real plugin code path with the Lark `drive.file.list` response shape mocked rather than a live multi-page folder. The `list` action was not exercised in the automated repro (its defect is structural: the schema exposes no `page_token` cursor, shown above), only `info` was driven end to end.

## Summary

Two distinct memory-wiki pages whose titles slugify to the same value silently overwrite each other, and the first page is permanently lost.

The agent-facing path is `wiki_apply` with op `create_synthesis`. When an agent saves a synthesis titled "Q3 Report" and later saves a different synthesis titled "Q3-Report", both resolve to `syntheses/q3-report.md` under id `synthesis.q3-report`. The second write overwrites the first: the first synthesis's managed Summary, sourceIds, claims, and confidence are gone, and neither `wiki_get` nor `wiki_search` can recover them. No error or warning is surfaced.

`slugifyWikiSegment` collapses case, spaces, and punctuation, so realistic agent-generated titles collide: "Q3 Report" / "Q3-Report", "Project Alpha!" / "Project Alpha", "Sales (2026)" / "Sales 2026", "Meeting Notes" / "meeting notes". The sibling CLI path `wiki ingest` has the same defect for `sources/<slug>.md`.

## Root cause

`extensions/memory-wiki/src/apply.ts` derived the synthesis page path and id from the bare slug, with no disambiguation when an existing page at that slug belongs to a different title:

```ts
// before
const slug = slugifyWikiSegment(params.mutation.title);
const pagePath = path.join("syntheses", `${slug}.md`).replace(/\\/g, "/");
const root = await fsRoot(params.config.vault.path);
const existing = await root.readText(pagePath).catch(() => "");
```

`slugifyWikiSegment` only appends a hash when the slug exceeds the byte cap (`extensions/memory-wiki/src/markdown.ts`), so short colliding titles get no hash. `ingest.ts` had the identical pattern for `source.<slug>`.

## Fix

Add one shared identity helper and route both writers through it. The plain readable slug is reused when it is free or already owns the same title (so re-applying a synthesis still updates in place); a distinct title that lands on an existing page gets a stable title-hash suffix, matching the existing `okf.ts` hashed-identity pattern:

```ts
// after (markdown.ts)
export async function resolveTitleKeyedWikiSlug(params: {
  title: string;
  readExistingTitleBySlug: (slug: string) => Promise<string | undefined>;
}): Promise<string> {
  const baseSlug = slugifyWikiSegment(params.title);
  const existingTitle = await params.readExistingTitleBySlug(baseSlug);
  if (existingTitle === undefined || existingTitle.trim() === params.title.trim()) {
    return baseSlug;
  }
  const suffix = createHash("sha1").update(params.title).digest("hex").slice(0, WIKI_SEGMENT_HASH_BYTES);
  return `${baseSlug}-${suffix}`;
}
```

`apply.ts` (`create_synthesis`) and `ingest.ts` (`wiki ingest`) both resolve their slug through this helper before reading/writing the page.

## Why this is the right boundary

- The helper lives next to `slugifyWikiSegment` and reuses the same `WIKI_SEGMENT_HASH_BYTES` and SHA-1 pattern already used by `okf.ts`/`createWikiPageFilename`. Two call sites share it (synthesis and source), so it pays rent.
- Backward compatible with no vault migration: the common single-page-per-title case keeps its plain `<slug>.md` path because the stored title matches. Only genuine distinct-title collisions get a hashed path, so existing vaults and same-title re-applies are unchanged.
- Prior art: closed PR #65992 proposed a source-path-keyed fix for the ingest half only and was closed unmerged; merged PR #64742 fixed only the Unicode/empty-slug case. Neither touched `create_synthesis`, and the distinct-title slug collision is still live on current `main` (proof below). This change fixes the agent-facing synthesis path that no prior PR addressed, and removes the same live collision from the source path with one helper.

## Verification

From a worktree with deps (node at /opt/node/bin):

- `node scripts/run-vitest.mjs extensions/memory-wiki/src/slug-collision.test.ts extensions/memory-wiki/src/apply.test.ts extensions/memory-wiki/src/ingest.test.ts extensions/memory-wiki/src/markdown.test.ts extensions/memory-wiki/src/query.test.ts` -> 53 passed
- New `slug-collision.test.ts` fails on pristine `main` (both synthesis and source collide onto one page) and passes with this patch.
- `node scripts/run-oxlint.mjs <changed files>` -> clean
- `oxfmt --check <changed files>` -> clean
- tsgo: the only error surfaced is a pre-existing unused import in `src/agents/model-picker-visibility.ts` on current `main` (unrelated to this extension change); no type error in the changed files.

## Real behavior proof

Behavior addressed: distinct memory-wiki syntheses/sources whose titles slugify equal no longer overwrite each other.
Real environment tested: drove the real `applyMemoryWikiMutation` (`create_synthesis`) against a temp vault on pristine `main` and on this patch with identical inputs, then read the vault from disk.
Exact steps or command run after this patch: apply `create_synthesis` "Q3 Report" (body "Revenue grew 12 percent"), then apply `create_synthesis` "Q3-Report" (body "Headcount fell 4 percent"); list `syntheses/` and check each page body.
Evidence after fix:
```
# BEFORE (pristine main 70023a1183)
synthesis page files: ["q3-report.md"]
  q3-report.md: revenue=false headcount=true
first synthesis (Q3 Report) recoverable: false

# AFTER (this patch, identical inputs)
synthesis page files: ["q3-report-97358135a013.md","q3-report.md"]
  q3-report-97358135a013.md: revenue=false headcount=true
  q3-report.md: revenue=true headcount=false
first synthesis (Q3 Report) recoverable: true
```
Observed result after fix: both syntheses persist as separate pages; the first synthesis's body, sourceIds, and claims are retained and recoverable.
What was not tested: a full `pnpm check`/`pnpm build` (OOM-prone box); two source files given an identical explicit title still merge by design, since title is the identity here.

## Summary

Selecting a native Z.ai model such as `zai/glm-5-turbo` can produce an OpenAI 401 at runtime even though OpenClaw logs the run as `provider=zai model=glm-5-turbo`. The resolved runtime model is missing the Z.ai `baseUrl`, so the OpenAI-compatible transport constructs the OpenAI SDK client without a base URL and appears to fall back to OpenAI's default API host.

## Observed behavior

A user reported:

- AlphaClaw UI/config changed primary from `anthropic/claude-opus-4-6` to `zai/glm-5-turbo`.
- Gateway startup says: `agent model: zai/glm-5-turbo`.
- Failed run says `provider=zai model=glm-5-turbo`.
- The 401 text is OpenAI's own error: `Incorrect API key provided... platform.openai.com/account/api-keys`.

This is consistent with OpenAI SDK default-host fallback, not with a request going to `https://api.z.ai/...`.

## Reproduction

Tested against both:

- installed AlphaClaw dependency: `openclaw@2026.5.28`
- latest npm release as of 2026-06-17: `openclaw@2026.6.8`

```js
import { resolveModel } from "./node_modules/openclaw/dist/model-CNcUE2JX.js";

const cfg = {
  agents: {
    defaults: {
      model: { primary: "zai/glm-5-turbo" },
      models: { "zai/glm-5-turbo": {} },
    },
  },
};

const result = resolveModel("zai", "glm-5-turbo", "/tmp/openclaw-agent-test", cfg);
console.log(JSON.stringify({
  error: result.error,
  model: result.model && {
    provider: result.model.provider,
    id: result.model.id,
    api: result.model.api,
    baseUrl: result.model.baseUrl,
  },
}, null, 2));
```

Actual output on `2026.6.8`:

```json
{
  "model": {
    "provider": "zai",
    "id": "glm-5-turbo",
    "api": "openai-completions"
  }
}
```

## Expected behavior

The resolved runtime model should include the manifest provider base URL:

```json
{
  "provider": "zai",
  "id": "glm-5-turbo",
  "api": "openai-completions",
  "baseUrl": "https://api.z.ai/api/paas/v4"
}
```

## Notes

The bundled Z.ai manifest/catalog does include the provider-level base URL and API:

```json
{
  "providers": {
    "zai": {
      "baseUrl": "https://api.z.ai/api/paas/v4",
      "api": "openai-completions"
    }
  }
}
```

Adding explicit provider config works around the issue:

```json
"models": {
  "providers": {
    "zai": {
      "baseUrl": "https://api.z.ai/api/paas/v4",
      "api": "openai-completions"
    }
  }
}
```

So this looks like the static manifest model resolution path is returning the model row without inheriting provider-level transport fields such as `baseUrl`.

## Impact

Users can successfully switch primary/default model to `zai/glm-5-turbo`, and status/logging shows the selected Z.ai provider/model, but runtime requests may authenticate against OpenAI instead of Z.ai, causing confusing OpenAI 401 errors.

## Summary

The inbound-media **writer** and the user-turn-transcript **reader** hold directly contradictory contracts for the parallel `Media*` arrays, so attachment content-types (and URLs) are assigned to the **wrong attachment** whenever an earlier attachment lacks a type/url.

**Writer** — `alignedStrings`, `src/channels/inbound-event/media.ts:35-42` (pads holes with `""` to *keep* index alignment):
```ts
function alignedStrings(values: Array<string | undefined>): string[] | undefined {
  if (!values.some(Boolean)) {
    return undefined;
  }
  // Preserve indexes across parallel Media* arrays so transcribed indexes and
  // media metadata continue to refer to the same attachment.
  return values.map((value) => value ?? "");
}
```

**Reader** — `normalizeOptionalTextArray`, `src/sessions/user-turn-transcript.ts:142-148`, called by `buildPersistedUserTurnMediaInputsFromFields` (`:176-178`) (drops the `""` holes, then indexes positionally):
```ts
function normalizeOptionalTextArray(
  values: readonly (string | null | undefined)[] | null | undefined,
): string[] {
  return (
    values?.map(normalizeOptionalText).filter((value): value is string => Boolean(value)) ?? []
  );
}
// :176-178
const paths = normalizeOptionalTextArray(fields.MediaPaths);
const urls = normalizeOptionalTextArray(fields.MediaUrls);
const types = normalizeOptionalTextArray(fields.MediaTypes);
```

Because one array gets compacted and another doesn't, index `i` no longer refers to the same attachment. Reached on every inbound media turn via `src/auto-reply/reply/get-reply-run.ts:1210` → `buildPersistedUserTurnMediaInputsFromFields(ctx)`.

## Impact

| Inbound (writer, index-aligned) | Persisted (after reader) | Correct |
|---|---|---|
| `a.bin` (no type), `b.png` (`image/png`) | `a.bin → image/png` ❌, `b.png → image/png` (right value, wrong reason) ❌ | `a.bin → undefined` (no derivable type), `b.png → image/png` |

A non-image attachment is mislabeled with a later attachment's MIME type; the real `image/png` is shifted off its true attachment (it lands on `b.png` only because compaction collapsed the array to a single element). The same failure hits `MediaUrls` when an earlier attachment has a path but no URL. **Severity: low–moderate** — it corrupts persisted transcript metadata (not message routing), and only on multi-attachment turns where an earlier attachment lacks a type/url (common for raw files/blobs). No crash, no message loss.

## Proposed fix

Stop compacting the parallel arrays in the reader — map per-index and let the `""` holes normalize to `undefined`, which the builder's existing per-index `??` lookups already treat as "absent":
```ts
function normalizeOptionalTextArray(
  values: readonly (string | null | undefined)[] | null | undefined,
): (string | undefined)[] {
  return values?.map(normalizeOptionalText) ?? [];
}
```
`buildPersistedUserTurnMediaInputsFromFields` is unchanged: it already derives `mediaCount` from `Math.max(paths.length, urls.length, …)` and reads each index with `types[index] ?? (index === 0 ? singleType : undefined)`, so an `undefined` hole falls through correctly and `mediaCount` becomes the true attachment count. The single-field fallbacks (`MediaType` at index 0) are unaffected.

**Sibling-contrast:** the writer (`alignedStrings`) and `MediaTranscribedIndexes` both go to explicit lengths specifically to keep index → attachment stable (the writer's comment: *"so transcribed indexes and media metadata continue to refer to the same attachment"*). The reader is the lone consumer that re-compacts, breaking the invariant the rest of the pipeline maintains.

**Provenance:** the writer's alignment-padding (`07f05e972e`) and the reader's compacting normalizer (`833520b13a`) were introduced in **separate refactors** and never reconciled.

## Reproduction (real exported reader, no mocks)

Input `{ MediaPaths: ["/media/a.bin","/media/b.png"], MediaTypes: ["","image/png"] }`.

Real output on **current main** (buggy):
```
OUT /media/a.bin => image/png      <-- WRONG (belongs to b.png)
OUT /media/b.png => image/png
```
Real output after the fix:
```
OUT /media/a.bin => undefined      <-- correct: no type borrowed from the next attachment
OUT /media/b.png => image/png
```

> Heads-up for triage: `src/sessions/user-turn-transcript.ts` is being actively refactored (a session-seam routing change plus several open PRs touch the file) — none touch `buildPersistedUserTurnMediaInputsFromFields`/`normalizeOptionalTextArray`, but the fix may want rebasing if that work lands first. I have a branch ready and am happy to open the PR.
